WEBVTT

00:01.836 --> 00:03.460
<i>- Last year,
a competition was created</i>

00:03.504 --> 00:05.629
<i>to test the nation's
best bladesmiths.</i>

00:05.673 --> 00:08.007
<i>Thousands responded,
and this year,</i>

00:08.050 --> 00:09.883
<i>craftsmen
from all over the country</i>

00:09.927 --> 00:11.802
<i>and all walks of life
have come forward</i>

00:11.846 --> 00:13.971
<i>for their chance
to claim the title.</i>

00:14.015 --> 00:15.556
- I'm gonna be the next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

00:15.599 --> 00:16.849
- I want to win!

00:16.892 --> 00:18.267
- It would be
a life-changing moment.

00:18.310 --> 00:19.977
- Welcome to the Forge.

00:20.021 --> 00:22.354
<i>Now the Forge returns
with challenges</i>

00:22.398 --> 00:24.773
<i>unlike anything
ever seen before.</i>

00:24.817 --> 00:26.650
You'll be using this.

00:26.694 --> 00:30.195
<i>Skill and ingenuity
will be pushed to the limit.</i>

00:30.239 --> 00:32.197
<i>Some will rise to the challenge.</i>

00:32.241 --> 00:34.575
<i>Some will fall,
but only the best</i>

00:34.618 --> 00:37.286
<i>will be crowned
"Forged in Fire" champions</i>

00:37.329 --> 00:39.580
<i>and take home $10,000.</i>

00:39.623 --> 00:42.583
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:42.626 --> 00:49.131
<i>¶ ¶</i>

00:49.175 --> 00:52.176
<i>- My name is Morgan Medland,
and I am 20 years old.</i>

00:52.219 --> 00:53.677
<i>If someone were to think</i>

00:53.721 --> 00:55.596
that I can't win
because I'm so young,

00:55.639 --> 00:57.598
all I have to say to them
is, "Just watch me."

00:57.641 --> 00:59.558
<i>- My name is Mardi Meshejian.</i>

00:59.602 --> 01:03.062
<i>I started as a jeweler,
but I just switched metals.</i>

01:03.105 --> 01:06.857
I like to push the boundaries
on what knives are.

01:06.901 --> 01:08.692
-<i> I'm Travis Wuertz.</i>

01:08.736 --> 01:10.903
I own a company
that manufactures accessories

01:10.946 --> 01:12.488
and tools for knife makers,

01:12.531 --> 01:16.075
<i>and I made my first real knife
when I was 12.</i>

01:16.118 --> 01:17.618
<i>- I'm Tom Ward.</i>

01:17.661 --> 01:19.495
<i>I am an architectural
fabricator.</i>

01:19.538 --> 01:24.249
My job entails making
fancy things for people

01:24.293 --> 01:26.168
who have more money than sense.

01:26.212 --> 01:27.711
<i>¶ ¶</i>

01:27.755 --> 01:30.714
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:30.758 --> 01:34.009
You are here to participate
in three rounds of competition

01:34.053 --> 01:35.893
designed to test every aspect

01:35.930 --> 01:38.347
of your edged weapon making
capabilities.

01:38.390 --> 01:40.140
At the end of each round,

01:40.184 --> 01:43.185
you will present your work
to our panel of expert judges.

01:43.229 --> 01:46.396
American Bladesmith Society
Master Smith, J. Neilson.

01:46.440 --> 01:50.109
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist, David Baker.

01:50.152 --> 01:53.612
Edged weapon specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:53.656 --> 01:56.448
They will decide which of you
is the "Forged in Fire" champion

01:56.492 --> 02:00.119
and leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

02:00.162 --> 02:03.539
All right, gents, this is
where things get exciting.

02:03.582 --> 02:06.208
In your first round
of competition,

02:06.252 --> 02:08.168
you'll be using this.

02:08.212 --> 02:11.171
<i>[tense music]</i>

02:11.215 --> 02:12.548
<i>¶ ¶</i>

02:12.591 --> 02:15.759
Your first round challenge
is to cut, saw,

02:15.803 --> 02:19.388
or disassemble from this car
all the materials you need

02:19.431 --> 02:21.140
to forge a blade
of your own design

02:21.183 --> 02:23.058
in your signature style.

02:23.102 --> 02:25.811
- [bleep], a car.

02:25.855 --> 02:28.063
[bleep].
[laughs]

02:28.107 --> 02:31.608
I do not typically
use car parts to make blades.

02:31.652 --> 02:32.985
- The blades themselves

02:33.028 --> 02:35.988
must fall within
the following parameters:

02:36.031 --> 02:38.240
<i>the length of the blade,
not including the tang,</i>

02:38.284 --> 02:41.160
<i>must be between 9 and 11 inches.</i>

02:41.203 --> 02:42.953
<i>The overall length
of your weapon</i>

02:42.997 --> 02:46.373
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:46.417 --> 02:48.000
Keeping up with the car theme,

02:48.043 --> 02:50.961
at the end of round two
your finished weapons

02:51.005 --> 02:52.379
will be tested and judged

02:52.423 --> 02:54.464
based on how they perform
in a tire slice

02:54.508 --> 02:57.676
<i>and their ability
to cut through jumper cables.</i>

02:57.720 --> 03:00.220
You will have four hours
to salvage your materials

03:00.264 --> 03:02.014
and forge your blades.

03:02.057 --> 03:05.267
Good luck, bladesmiths,
you'll need it.

03:05.311 --> 03:08.353
Your time starts... now.

03:08.397 --> 03:11.106
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:11.150 --> 03:13.150
Which metal
would you go for, Jay?

03:13.194 --> 03:15.319
- I'd be going
for the coil springs.

03:15.362 --> 03:16.737
- Dave?

03:16.780 --> 03:18.113
- Either the coil springs
or the axles.

03:18.157 --> 03:19.997
- Doug?
- I'd go for the tires.

03:20.034 --> 03:22.451
We use rubber knives
for training.

03:22.494 --> 03:23.619
- [laughs]

03:23.662 --> 03:25.162
So immediately these guys

03:25.206 --> 03:27.039
look like they're
on the NASCAR circuit.

03:27.082 --> 03:29.541
They're just ripping the tires
off of these vehicles.

03:29.585 --> 03:32.711
- I've never directly
pulled pieces off a car

03:32.755 --> 03:34.546
<i>for my own use.</i>

03:34.590 --> 03:38.884
The piece of metal that I go for
is the coil spring.

03:38.928 --> 03:40.677
<i>Brute force and ignorance.</i>

03:40.721 --> 03:42.888
[laughs]

03:42.932 --> 03:44.723
- Tom got that out
in record time.

03:44.767 --> 03:46.516
- He certainly did.

03:46.560 --> 03:49.228
<i>- The weapon I'm making
is a competition cutter,</i>

03:49.271 --> 03:51.980
<i>which has a big, like,
very brutal blade.</i>

03:52.024 --> 03:53.357
<i>Very robust.</i>

03:53.400 --> 03:55.275
And I'm thinking
that the challenges

03:55.319 --> 03:58.904
that they've issued us would
require a really robust blade.

03:58.948 --> 04:02.282
The plan is
to take all the pieces

04:02.326 --> 04:04.451
of spring, uncoil them,

04:04.495 --> 04:07.287
and then assemble them
into a construction

04:07.331 --> 04:09.122
that I can forge weld
into a bar.

04:09.166 --> 04:11.458
- It's not gonna be easy
to get those loose parts

04:11.502 --> 04:13.126
forged into a billet.

04:13.170 --> 04:14.920
<i>- If I don't get this billet
done properly,</i>

04:14.964 --> 04:17.756
<i>everything that I do
in the next steps</i>

04:17.800 --> 04:20.884
could possibly fail and put me
out of the competition.

04:20.928 --> 04:24.221
<i>¶ ¶</i>

04:24.265 --> 04:27.182
- All right, guys,
coming in hot on this side.

04:27.226 --> 04:29.810
<i>I've made several blades
from car parts.</i>

04:29.853 --> 04:32.145
Actually, most of the blades
I started off making

04:32.189 --> 04:36.483
were made from leaf springs
from large tractors and cars.

04:36.527 --> 04:40.612
I'm making a large
chopper-hunter mash up,

04:40.656 --> 04:42.447
is I guess
what you would call it.

04:42.491 --> 04:45.534
<i>It's got a spear tip point on it</i>

04:45.577 --> 04:48.036
and excellent chopping
capabilities.

04:48.080 --> 04:49.788
<i>My game plan is to work</i>

04:49.832 --> 04:52.082
<i>as fast as I possibly can
without messing up.</i>

04:52.126 --> 04:53.292
What's up?

04:53.335 --> 04:54.668
- What are you aiming for?

04:54.712 --> 04:56.169
I'm looking at
that rod in there.

04:56.213 --> 04:57.671
- I'm looking at the spring.

04:57.715 --> 05:00.090
- I got a spring off the back.

05:00.134 --> 05:01.591
- Do you?
- Yeah.

05:01.635 --> 05:03.135
I'd rather try to get
one of these and...

05:03.178 --> 05:05.012
- Here.
Yeah, I'll go take the back one.

05:05.055 --> 05:07.556
You take this one.
- Yeah.

05:07.599 --> 05:09.308
- Mardi went ahead
and told Morgan

05:09.351 --> 05:10.559
to take his coil spring,

05:10.602 --> 05:12.436
and he's going for the axle.

05:12.479 --> 05:15.272
<i>- I'm pretty resourceful
with auto parts.</i>

05:15.316 --> 05:17.649
I've done that much
in my career.

05:17.693 --> 05:21.361
<i>I just didn't want to mess
with too many pieces.</i>

05:21.405 --> 05:23.530
Coil springs can be very skinny,

05:23.574 --> 05:26.616
<i>so I would have to
cut that into pieces</i>

05:26.660 --> 05:28.744
<i>and combine it
and put it together,</i>

05:28.787 --> 05:31.413
and it seems like a lot of work.

05:31.457 --> 05:34.333
<i>I'm going to make a nice seax.</i>

05:34.376 --> 05:36.418
<i>I wanted to make
a nice, beefy cutting blade.</i>

05:36.462 --> 05:38.086
<i>That way it has a lot of support</i>

05:38.130 --> 05:40.297
for going through
difficult material

05:40.341 --> 05:43.175
like tire and jumper cables.

05:43.218 --> 05:44.885
<i>¶ ¶</i>

05:44.928 --> 05:48.138
- Oh, man,
that's a railroad hammer.

05:48.182 --> 05:51.141
<i>¶ ¶</i>

05:51.185 --> 05:53.602
- So Travis is getting
that coil spring.

05:53.645 --> 05:55.520
- It looks like they all went
for the coil springs,

05:55.564 --> 05:57.189
except Mardi.

05:57.232 --> 05:59.358
<i>- I'm going to make
a recurved blade.</i>

05:59.401 --> 06:01.943
<i>Definitely some
Persian influence.</i>

06:01.987 --> 06:05.280
Nothing chops
quite like a recurved.

06:05.324 --> 06:07.532
<i>I go ahead and go
for the coil springs</i>

06:07.576 --> 06:09.326
<i>'cause once I have the torch</i>

06:09.370 --> 06:11.328
I know I can just cut
those suckers right down there,

06:11.372 --> 06:12.621
make whatever loops.

06:12.664 --> 06:13.830
They'll all be the same length.

06:13.874 --> 06:15.415
I'll straighten the suckers out.

06:15.459 --> 06:17.000
I'll forge weld
the sons of bitches together,

06:17.044 --> 06:18.627
and I have a blade.

06:18.670 --> 06:21.254
<i>But I just keep having
problems with the torch.</i>

06:21.298 --> 06:23.757
Fire, fire, fire!

06:23.801 --> 06:25.550
[chuckles]

06:25.594 --> 06:27.219
- Well, it's a good thing
we have fire safety

06:27.262 --> 06:29.388
on standby today.

06:29.431 --> 06:31.723
<i>¶ ¶</i>

06:31.767 --> 06:33.767
- Travis is back
on the hot wrench.

06:33.811 --> 06:35.310
- The thing is, we've seen
that the hot wrench

06:35.354 --> 06:36.895
is a slow way to do this,

06:36.939 --> 06:38.939
that there's a lot
of flammable material

06:38.982 --> 06:40.732
left around that piece.

06:40.776 --> 06:42.275
Go to the grinder.
- Yeah.

06:42.319 --> 06:45.195
- Cut to the chase.

06:45.239 --> 06:48.073
<i>- That took a little longer
than I meant to,</i>

06:48.117 --> 06:50.951
but now I can stack up
as much as I can

06:50.994 --> 06:53.829
and... and hope for the best.

06:53.872 --> 06:57.290
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

06:57.334 --> 06:59.960
You have three hours remaining!

07:00.003 --> 07:03.797
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:03.841 --> 07:06.466
- I am incredibly relieved
right now

07:06.510 --> 07:08.385
that this piece
of steel is solid.

07:08.429 --> 07:10.095
<i>I'm getting less stressed,</i>

07:10.139 --> 07:12.681
and I'm getting more excited
about the piece.

07:12.724 --> 07:16.852
<i>¶ ¶</i>

07:16.895 --> 07:18.437
- Well, if we're going
by the beard competition,

07:18.480 --> 07:20.647
Tom is way ahead of everyone.

07:20.691 --> 07:22.232
He's got that awesome beard.

07:22.276 --> 07:23.984
- Oh, there it goes!
- Which he just tucked in.

07:24.027 --> 07:26.194
- That's how he keeps it.

07:27.614 --> 07:35.412
<i>¶ ¶</i>

07:35.456 --> 07:37.330
- Oh, [bleep].

07:37.374 --> 07:41.209
- Oh, we got... we got a hot mess
happening over here.

07:41.253 --> 07:43.962
<i>- It's still not
sticking together</i>

07:44.006 --> 07:46.006
as well as what I need it to.

07:46.049 --> 07:48.508
- Oh, wow.
- Oh, man.

07:48.552 --> 07:50.385
- All the gaps in between there,

07:50.429 --> 07:52.095
you can't just force 'em closed.

07:52.139 --> 07:54.431
- Yeah, that's... yeah.
- You gotta work them out.

07:54.475 --> 07:57.476
He's really got to change
his game plan up.

07:57.519 --> 07:59.895
- I don't want to be seen as,
like, some little, young punk

07:59.938 --> 08:02.230
who thought he could do this
but really can't.

08:02.274 --> 08:05.400
<i>[tense music]</i>

08:05.444 --> 08:07.444
<i>An hour and a half has passed by</i>

08:07.488 --> 08:10.739
and I've decided to
just scrap my first project.

08:10.782 --> 08:13.617
It's not worth the time
that I'm putting into it.

08:13.660 --> 08:17.120
<i>So I'm gonna go ahead and
cut another solid piece off.</i>

08:17.164 --> 08:19.289
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:19.333 --> 08:20.957
- This is a smart move.
- Very smart.

08:21.001 --> 08:24.753
- A smart move
by a young competitor.

08:24.796 --> 08:28.048
<i>- I'm behind these other guys,
starting over fresh,</i>

08:28.091 --> 08:29.716
and I've really got
to pick things up

08:29.760 --> 08:33.261
and forge
and move a lot of metal.

08:33.305 --> 08:36.223
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:36.266 --> 08:39.059
- Well, looks like Mardi's
way ahead of the competition.

08:39.102 --> 08:40.435
- Mardi's steel
is looking great.

08:40.479 --> 08:41.978
- Yeah.

08:42.022 --> 08:43.813
- Heck, he could just go
to the grinder right now.

08:43.857 --> 08:47.275
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:47.319 --> 08:49.819
- He's got a lot of those
heavy hammer marks to grind out

08:49.863 --> 08:51.655
and it takes time.

08:51.698 --> 08:53.365
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:53.408 --> 08:55.575
- [bleep].

08:55.619 --> 08:57.244
- What is that?

08:57.287 --> 08:59.704
- Oh, no, he's got
a chip in the edge.

08:59.748 --> 09:01.373
Do you see that?
- Oh, yeah.

09:01.416 --> 09:04.918
- Oh, it's a grinder bite.

09:04.962 --> 09:08.421
- One of the aluminum wheels
bumped the bevel of the blade

09:08.465 --> 09:11.716
and made a little...
A little blemish there,

09:11.760 --> 09:14.219
<i>but I still have plenty
of meat in the blade</i>

09:14.263 --> 09:18.598
to clean that up
and take care of it.

09:18.642 --> 09:22.018
<i>¶ ¶</i>

09:22.062 --> 09:25.188
- I'm regretting my decision
to use the coil springs

09:25.232 --> 09:27.357
<i>and forge welding them together.</i>

09:27.401 --> 09:29.859
Son of a [bleep].

09:29.903 --> 09:31.695
Ah.

09:31.738 --> 09:34.864
- Travis is really
fighting with that billet.

09:34.908 --> 09:38.201
<i>- I just keep seeing
little problems with it.</i>

09:38.245 --> 09:39.744
[bleep].

09:39.788 --> 09:42.622
I think I'm going home.

09:42.666 --> 09:45.375
- Travis is in trouble now.
- Yeah.

09:45.419 --> 09:47.711
- [bleep] this.

09:47.754 --> 09:50.839
Just too [bleep] stupid.
Just too [bleep] stupid.

09:58.849 --> 10:01.391
-<i> Once I got to forge welding,</i>

10:01.435 --> 10:04.352
I didn't really stick my pieces
together very well.

10:04.396 --> 10:07.314
- Travis is really
fighting with that billet.

10:09.109 --> 10:13.653
- Once I see that basically
everybody is done forging,

10:13.697 --> 10:17.574
<i>and I still have pieces
of coil spring</i>

10:17.618 --> 10:19.034
that are just...

10:19.077 --> 10:21.411
not sticking...

10:21.455 --> 10:22.787
All right.

10:22.831 --> 10:24.456
I tossed that sucker.

10:24.499 --> 10:25.832
- Gone.

10:25.876 --> 10:27.000
- He's done.
He's done with that.

10:27.044 --> 10:28.001
- Way to go.

10:28.045 --> 10:31.004
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:31.048 --> 10:33.632
<i>¶ ¶</i>

10:33.675 --> 10:36.718
Travis has one big hunk
of axle there.

10:36.762 --> 10:40.138
I have no doubt he's gonna get
that piece of metal hot

10:40.182 --> 10:42.557
and just start
drawing it out beautifully.

10:42.601 --> 10:44.267
<i>- It's a fresh start,</i>

10:44.311 --> 10:45.894
solid steel,

10:45.937 --> 10:47.354
<i>but I ain't got much time.</i>

10:47.397 --> 10:50.565
- Bladesmiths, you have
90 minutes remaining!

10:50.609 --> 10:51.900
90 minutes!

10:51.943 --> 10:53.818
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:53.862 --> 10:55.570
<i>- I'm going to heat treat,</i>

10:55.614 --> 10:58.365
and I'm going to be incredibly
cautious in my setup.

10:58.408 --> 11:01.618
<i>I made sure the oil
was screaming hot.</i>

11:03.330 --> 11:04.371
- We got a quench.

11:07.250 --> 11:10.585
- Oh, he's got a little bend
in it, it looks like.

11:10.629 --> 11:12.253
- He kept heating that blade

11:12.297 --> 11:14.673
on the outside of the forge
on one side and not both.

11:14.716 --> 11:17.676
- But he has an hour
to fix that.

11:17.719 --> 11:20.970
- So now it's a real
[bleep] blade.

11:21.014 --> 11:23.515
I don't know how the [bleep]
that happened.

11:23.558 --> 11:26.601
<i>¶ ¶</i>

11:26.645 --> 11:28.937
<i>- I feel like I'm definitely
back in the game.</i>

11:28.980 --> 11:30.980
I'm definitely
feeling better now.

11:31.024 --> 11:34.734
- Look how quickly Morgan
came out with that shape.

11:34.778 --> 11:36.653
<i>¶ ¶</i>

11:36.697 --> 11:38.363
<i>- The most important part
of this blade</i>

11:38.407 --> 11:40.323
is gonna be getting
the heat treat correct

11:40.367 --> 11:43.326
<i>and not pinging
or cracking the blade at all.</i>

11:43.370 --> 11:45.078
- There he is,
he's in the quench

11:45.122 --> 11:46.955
and that looked beautiful.
- Morgan's in the quench.

11:46.998 --> 11:48.540
<i>- I didn't feel any pings</i>

11:48.583 --> 11:51.334
and the blade stayed
very, very straight.

11:51.378 --> 11:54.087
I'm very happy
I didn't mess up again.

11:54.131 --> 11:55.463
[chuckles]

11:55.507 --> 11:57.799
That would have killed me.
- This is great.

11:57.843 --> 12:00.427
We're seeing people take
the time with their quench.

12:00.470 --> 12:02.512
This should always
be done this way,

12:02.556 --> 12:05.306
as opposed to these
speed quenches

12:05.350 --> 12:08.184
that we constantly see
that make me so crazy.

12:08.228 --> 12:10.812
- There we go,
Travis in the oil.

12:10.856 --> 12:13.565
<i>- Once I threw away
my first blade</i>

12:13.608 --> 12:16.317
and had nice steel
to start with,

12:16.361 --> 12:19.237
<i>I had no problem.</i>

12:19.281 --> 12:20.864
- 15 minutes!

12:20.907 --> 12:25.326
Bladesmiths, you have
15 minutes remaining!

12:25.370 --> 12:28.496
<i>- I didn't realize they all
already quenched their blades.</i>

12:28.540 --> 12:32.375
I have to start thinking
about when I'm doing mine.

12:32.419 --> 12:35.670
- The big question right now
is Mardi with this heat treat.

12:35.714 --> 12:39.174
He's got a very, very thin,
very wide blade.

12:39.217 --> 12:41.509
There's a lot
that can go on there.

12:41.553 --> 12:44.637
If he ends up with a problem,
he's gonna have to fix it fast.

12:44.681 --> 12:47.599
<i>¶ ¶</i>

12:47.642 --> 12:48.933
All right, we got a quench.

12:48.977 --> 12:50.727
- Good.

12:50.771 --> 12:52.812
- Well, we got a nod.

12:52.856 --> 12:54.898
- Oh, that looks pretty good.

12:54.941 --> 12:56.733
<i>- I'm feeling great.</i>

12:56.777 --> 12:58.943
I've got this.

12:58.987 --> 13:01.571
- Ten, nine, eight...

13:01.615 --> 13:03.114
- It's very sharp.

13:03.158 --> 13:05.992
Took all that hair off my arm.
[chuckles]

13:06.036 --> 13:09.704
- Five, four, three,

13:09.748 --> 13:11.790
two, one.

13:11.833 --> 13:15.043
Bladesmiths, time is up.

13:15.086 --> 13:17.128
Please stop all work.

13:17.172 --> 13:18.838
- Good man.
- Hey.

13:18.882 --> 13:20.757
- That was fun.
- Great job.

13:20.801 --> 13:22.717
<i>- Time's up,
and I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

13:22.761 --> 13:25.011
I'm pretty excited to see
what they have to say about it.

13:25.055 --> 13:27.889
- I have a perfectly good,
operational blade.

13:27.933 --> 13:30.266
It doesn't have
quite the finish and stuff

13:30.310 --> 13:32.811
that I would normally
like to do,

13:32.854 --> 13:36.356
<i>but overall,
I'm pretty happy with it.</i>

13:37.859 --> 13:40.819
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

13:40.862 --> 13:41.945
<i>¶ ¶</i>

13:41.988 --> 13:43.029
- Bladesmiths,

13:43.073 --> 13:44.823
your first round challenge

13:44.866 --> 13:47.700
was to harvest usable steel
from a wrecked car

13:47.744 --> 13:51.788
to build a signature blade
of your own design.

13:51.832 --> 13:54.916
Tom, please present your blade
to the judges.

13:54.960 --> 13:58.336
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:58.380 --> 14:00.547
-<i> Well, Tom, it's so clean</i>

14:00.590 --> 14:02.799
and this is still round one.

14:02.843 --> 14:04.801
Kudos for going the extra mile

14:04.845 --> 14:07.345
to turn in a beautiful piece.

14:07.389 --> 14:09.681
- You went as far
as to sharpen this edge.

14:09.724 --> 14:12.225
That could be dangerous
going into round two.

14:12.269 --> 14:15.395
Are you a little worried
about going into a second round

14:15.438 --> 14:17.939
and having to deal
with that blade?

14:17.983 --> 14:20.358
- I'll just tape it up.
It'll be fine.

14:20.402 --> 14:21.901
- Brave man.

14:21.945 --> 14:23.403
- [chuckles]

14:23.446 --> 14:26.155
- Travis, you're up next.

14:26.199 --> 14:28.658
<i>¶ ¶</i>

14:28.702 --> 14:30.285
<i>- When you initially started</i>

14:30.328 --> 14:32.078
<i>with the coil spring,</i>

14:32.122 --> 14:33.413
it looked like maybe you were

14:33.456 --> 14:34.831
getting a little
impatient with it

14:34.875 --> 14:36.457
and then started
trying to force it.

14:36.501 --> 14:37.667
What happened?

14:37.711 --> 14:41.129
- [bleep] happened.
A lot.

14:41.172 --> 14:43.464
- Once you shifted
gears, though,

14:43.508 --> 14:46.259
you had this shaped
within 20 minutes.

14:46.303 --> 14:48.386
Good job.

14:48.430 --> 14:51.514
- Mardi, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:51.558 --> 14:54.809
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:54.853 --> 14:57.520
<i>- Mardi, I like the seax design.</i>

14:57.564 --> 15:01.107
For such a broad knife,
it's thin and light.

15:01.151 --> 15:03.693
And as I always say, it doesn't
have to be thick and heavy

15:03.737 --> 15:06.571
to be a strong knife,
so nicely done.

15:06.615 --> 15:08.197
- Thank you.

15:08.241 --> 15:11.659
- I saw at one point you
kind of hit a spot down here,

15:11.703 --> 15:12.952
got a big wiggle in it.

15:12.996 --> 15:14.836
- When I was tapering the tang,

15:14.873 --> 15:16.956
I bumped into one
of the aluminum drive wheels.

15:17.000 --> 15:19.167
- Gotcha, okay.

15:19.210 --> 15:20.919
Well done.

15:20.962 --> 15:24.714
- Morgan, please present
your blade to the judges.

15:24.758 --> 15:27.884
<i>¶ ¶</i>

15:27.928 --> 15:31.304
- Well, I gotta say,
you got some skills.

15:31.348 --> 15:32.597
- Thank you.

15:32.641 --> 15:35.016
- You do have
a slight bit of a twist

15:35.060 --> 15:37.018
<i>when looking down the blade,</i>

15:37.062 --> 15:40.063
but it's nothing really big.

15:40.106 --> 15:44.025
- Well, Morgan, the choices
you made show such maturity

15:44.069 --> 15:45.818
in the skills that you do.

15:45.862 --> 15:48.422
It goes to show that you
don't have to be an old guy

15:48.448 --> 15:50.114
to be able to make great blades.

15:50.158 --> 15:52.825
That's beautiful to see,
especially with the craft

15:52.869 --> 15:55.828
that we're trying
to push over here.

15:55.872 --> 15:58.748
- Would anybody
lend me a knife, please?

15:58.792 --> 16:00.208
[laughter]

16:00.251 --> 16:02.251
- Well, bladesmiths,

16:02.295 --> 16:05.254
the judges now need some time
to make a decision.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.423
Thank you.

16:07.467 --> 16:09.467
<i>¶ ¶</i>

16:10.553 --> 16:13.513
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:13.556 --> 16:15.723
<i>¶ ¶</i>

16:15.767 --> 16:17.475
- It's nice to sit down,
finally.

16:17.519 --> 16:19.352
- Right?

16:19.396 --> 16:23.106
- Okay, judges, these
are the most finished blades

16:23.149 --> 16:26.150
we've ever had come out
of round one, as a group.

16:26.194 --> 16:29.362
Let's go ahead and start
with Tom's blade on the end.

16:29.406 --> 16:32.365
- He's actually given us
a bit of a false edge

16:32.409 --> 16:34.200
up on the tip here.

16:34.244 --> 16:37.245
Not sharp, but sharp enough
that it's gonna, you know,

16:37.288 --> 16:39.706
split that rubber
when it goes into the tire.

16:39.749 --> 16:42.709
He's obviously designed
for the challenges.

16:42.752 --> 16:46.587
- All right, let's move on
to Travis' blade.

16:46.631 --> 16:48.297
-<i> I've got to give props.</i>

16:48.341 --> 16:50.466
This is a round one challenge,

16:50.510 --> 16:53.094
and he's turned in
an almost finished blade.

16:53.138 --> 16:55.471
- He did a very nice job
on the grind,

16:55.515 --> 16:58.641
and, you know, the finish
is just beautiful.

16:58.685 --> 17:01.352
- I think my chances are good.
I got a blade.

17:01.396 --> 17:04.981
It's hard and meets
the length requirements.

17:05.025 --> 17:07.567
<i>- Let's move on
to Mardi's blade.</i>

17:07.610 --> 17:10.194
- I like where
Mardi is going with this,

17:10.238 --> 17:14.282
but his plunge grinds
are extremely off-center.

17:14.325 --> 17:15.867
- Oh, yeah.

17:15.910 --> 17:18.703
All in all, there are
defects in this blade

17:18.747 --> 17:21.307
that I'm not seeing
in the other two

17:21.332 --> 17:23.875
that we've looked at so far.

17:23.918 --> 17:27.003
- All right, let's talk
about Morgan's blade.

17:27.047 --> 17:28.588
- Got the integral guard.

17:28.631 --> 17:29.839
I mean, it's a little bit off,

17:29.883 --> 17:31.215
<i>but that's easy to clean up</i>

17:31.259 --> 17:33.551
<i>during the fitting up process.</i>

17:33.595 --> 17:35.636
Little bit of a twist
in the blade.

17:35.680 --> 17:37.430
In a lot of our challenges

17:37.474 --> 17:40.516
that we've had in the past
those would be acceptable,

17:40.560 --> 17:43.352
but the bar
has been raised here.

17:43.396 --> 17:46.981
- So, judges,
have you made a decision?

17:47.025 --> 17:48.649
- Yeah.

17:48.693 --> 17:50.860
- All right,
let's go tell our smiths.

17:50.904 --> 17:53.863
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

17:53.907 --> 17:57.241
<i>¶ ¶</i>

17:57.285 --> 17:59.827
Well, bladesmiths,
the quality of work

17:59.871 --> 18:01.329
that you turned in

18:01.372 --> 18:03.331
has made this
one of the toughest decisions

18:03.374 --> 18:05.958
the judges have
ever had to make.

18:06.002 --> 18:14.002
<i>¶ ¶</i>

18:14.260 --> 18:15.676
Mardi,

18:15.720 --> 18:18.638
your blade did not make the cut.

18:18.681 --> 18:21.516
- Each and every one of you
turned in a beautiful blade,

18:21.559 --> 18:24.894
and it's because of that we had
to look at the finer details.

18:24.938 --> 18:27.355
Your plunge grinds were uneven,

18:27.398 --> 18:30.608
and there were more creases
and visible waves on your blade

18:30.652 --> 18:32.068
compared to the others,

18:32.112 --> 18:34.487
and for that we have
to let you go.

18:34.531 --> 18:36.447
- Thank you for the opportunity.

18:36.491 --> 18:40.243
- Mardi, please
surrender your weapon.

18:40.286 --> 18:42.161
-<i> I'm sad to go,</i>

18:42.205 --> 18:44.705
but I feel I did my best,

18:44.749 --> 18:47.708
<i>and I think I did myself,
my craft,</i>

18:47.752 --> 18:51.504
and everything
I represent justice.

18:51.548 --> 18:54.048
<i>¶ ¶</i>

18:54.092 --> 18:56.843
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.

18:56.886 --> 18:59.178
You've made it through
to the second round.

18:59.222 --> 19:01.806
Your challenge is to craft
and attach a handle

19:01.850 --> 19:03.641
to your blades using the range

19:03.685 --> 19:05.268
of materials provided to you,

19:05.311 --> 19:07.645
turning them into
fully functional weapons.

19:07.689 --> 19:09.814
You will have three hours
for this round.

19:09.858 --> 19:12.692
You can use that time
to address any flaws or issues

19:12.735 --> 19:15.945
that were identified
with your blades.

19:15.989 --> 19:19.323
It will then be tested
for strength and durability,

19:19.367 --> 19:21.701
<i>slicing through a car tire</i>

19:21.744 --> 19:23.911
<i>and cutting through
jumper cables.</i>

19:23.955 --> 19:26.873
I'll remind you,
at the end of this round,

19:26.916 --> 19:28.624
one of you must
surrender his weapon

19:28.668 --> 19:30.376
and leave the Forge.

19:30.420 --> 19:33.796
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your time starts now.

19:33.840 --> 19:35.214
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:35.258 --> 19:38.092
- And here we go.
- All right.

19:38.136 --> 19:39.802
- The shop is like a pool table,

19:39.846 --> 19:42.847
and we got three balls bouncing
around the corner pockets.

19:42.891 --> 19:44.599
<i>- I really want to make a handle</i>

19:44.642 --> 19:47.560
that gives the blade
a chance to perform...

19:47.604 --> 19:49.395
Oh, there we go.
Now we're talking.

19:49.439 --> 19:52.565
And the black micarta
that I'm going with

19:52.609 --> 19:56.360
<i>is some of the most
durable material available.</i>

19:56.404 --> 19:58.112
- There's a sidestep
and do-si-do.

19:58.156 --> 19:59.363
- You saw that, right?

19:59.407 --> 20:02.033
- Yeah.
- Nice pirouette.

20:02.076 --> 20:03.701
- I try.

20:03.745 --> 20:05.161
<i>[rock music]</i>

20:05.205 --> 20:06.996
- Let there be fire.

20:07.040 --> 20:11.542
<i>¶ ¶</i>

20:11.586 --> 20:14.086
- There's always a chance
for things to go wrong.

20:14.130 --> 20:16.839
Don't you break on me,
you mother[bleep] bit.

20:16.883 --> 20:18.507
<i>I don't even keep track
of the things</i>

20:18.551 --> 20:21.969
<i>that go wrong anymore.</i>

20:22.013 --> 20:23.554
<i>It just happens.</i>

20:23.598 --> 20:25.389
You adapt, you move on,

20:25.433 --> 20:28.935
you find another blade,
and you don't stop.

20:28.978 --> 20:31.020
Just keep building.
Just keep building.

20:31.064 --> 20:32.480
Just keep building.

20:32.523 --> 20:35.233
<i>- I am making
a three-piece knife,</i>

20:35.276 --> 20:37.693
<i>which is called that because
it's just the knife blade</i>

20:37.737 --> 20:40.821
and then two handle scales
on either side.

20:40.865 --> 20:42.782
<i>The KISS principle:</i>

20:42.825 --> 20:44.575
keep it simple, stupid.

20:44.619 --> 20:45.993
<i>¶ ¶</i>

20:46.037 --> 20:47.745
<i>I stopped working on my handle</i>

20:47.789 --> 20:51.332
so that I could go regrind
my point to make it stabbier.

20:51.376 --> 20:53.251
- Reprofiling on the tip
of Tom's knife.

20:53.294 --> 20:56.295
- Want to make sure
you got a good point.

20:56.339 --> 20:58.589
- Stabbier is definitely
a technical term.

20:58.633 --> 21:00.883
[laughs]

21:00.927 --> 21:02.260
<i>[rock music]</i>

21:02.303 --> 21:04.011
- My strategy this round

21:04.055 --> 21:05.680
is, I'm gonna look
for a stabilized wood block

21:05.723 --> 21:07.431
<i>and make a comfortable handle.</i>

21:07.475 --> 21:09.433
<i>¶ ¶</i>

21:09.477 --> 21:11.394
I need to put
some sort of guard on it,

21:11.437 --> 21:13.729
<i>so that's gonna pose an issue.</i>

21:13.773 --> 21:15.106
That is insanely prettier.

21:15.149 --> 21:16.649
<i>It's all down to the details,</i>

21:16.693 --> 21:18.943
and I need to make sure
I get these details right.

21:18.987 --> 21:20.945
I added this piece in here.

21:20.989 --> 21:23.489
That way when you're stabbing,
your hand doesn't slide forward.

21:23.533 --> 21:25.032
I needed more metal.

21:25.076 --> 21:28.411
- Bladesmiths, you have
only two hours remaining

21:28.454 --> 21:29.870
to finish your work.

21:29.914 --> 21:33.291
<i>[rock music]</i>

21:33.334 --> 21:34.792
- Yeah.

21:34.836 --> 21:37.420
The glue-up is always
a moment of tension,

21:37.463 --> 21:39.213
<i>because you're dealing
with a material</i>

21:39.257 --> 21:41.465
that's setting
and you can't stop it.

21:41.509 --> 21:43.217
And so once
the chemical reaction starts,

21:43.261 --> 21:46.095
<i>it's...
You just got to get it done.</i>

21:46.139 --> 21:48.889
<i>¶ ¶</i>

21:48.933 --> 21:51.100
[bleep].

21:51.144 --> 21:52.893
[groans]

21:52.937 --> 21:55.187
I crack the front of the scale.

21:55.231 --> 21:57.732
- Tom made a crucial mistake.

21:57.775 --> 21:59.900
- I might be screwed.

21:59.944 --> 22:01.444
Ugh, [bleep].

22:09.954 --> 22:11.495
<i>[intense music]</i>

22:11.539 --> 22:12.913
<i>- This is the big moment.</i>

22:12.957 --> 22:14.877
It's time
to clamp the scales down.

22:14.917 --> 22:16.709
The glue's on.

22:16.753 --> 22:21.047
<i>¶ ¶</i>

22:21.090 --> 22:22.506
[bleep]!

22:22.550 --> 22:27.428
<i>I crack the front of the scale.</i>

22:27.472 --> 22:30.181
I can see that the piece
is fractured cleanly,

22:30.224 --> 22:31.557
and if I get the handle scales

22:31.601 --> 22:33.517
<i>flat and flush
down onto the knife</i>

22:33.561 --> 22:35.361
I can just hold it there
while the epoxy sets,

22:35.396 --> 22:38.105
and it'll be totally fine.

22:38.149 --> 22:42.026
<i>¶ ¶</i>

22:42.070 --> 22:46.030
- This guy moves at
110 miles an hour

22:46.074 --> 22:47.573
at all times.

22:47.617 --> 22:49.325
- It might look like
I'm running frantic...

22:49.369 --> 22:51.327
At least if I sweat enough,
I won't have to piss.

22:51.371 --> 22:53.162
<i>I just don't like wasting time.</i>

22:53.206 --> 22:55.289
You count my steps,

22:55.333 --> 22:56.916
<i>I bet I put a couple miles in.</i>

22:56.959 --> 23:00.586
- He might be a little bit
of a mad genius.

23:00.630 --> 23:02.963
- Do I have an extra?
Huh.

23:03.007 --> 23:04.548
- We'll see.

23:04.592 --> 23:07.551
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:07.595 --> 23:09.428
<i>¶ ¶</i>

23:09.472 --> 23:11.931
<i>- I have most of my rough
grinding done on my handles.</i>

23:11.974 --> 23:13.599
Now it's time
to pull my pieces apart

23:13.643 --> 23:15.601
and glue them all together.

23:15.645 --> 23:18.020
- My problem with this technique

23:18.064 --> 23:19.313
that Morgan's using

23:19.357 --> 23:21.107
is he's gonna
be putting big dents

23:21.150 --> 23:22.608
in that handle material

23:22.652 --> 23:27.279
right where it matches up
with his tang.

23:27.323 --> 23:29.031
- [bleep] damn it.

23:29.075 --> 23:32.243
- He just cracked his material.
He just broke his handle.

23:32.286 --> 23:34.578
- That's it.
- Oh, crap.

23:34.622 --> 23:36.247
- Cut it off,
back to square one.

23:36.290 --> 23:37.998
- Mm-hmm.

23:38.042 --> 23:40.209
- I can just glue that little
piece right back in place

23:40.253 --> 23:42.253
and it should just
lock right back in.

23:42.296 --> 23:44.255
I hate this part, waiting.

23:44.298 --> 23:46.424
Sucks.

23:46.467 --> 23:50.177
- Bladesmiths, you have
just 30 minutes remaining

23:50.221 --> 23:53.139
to finish your work.

23:53.182 --> 23:55.057
- Hey, Tom, if I change the
belts, am I gonna mess with you?

23:55.101 --> 23:56.517
- No, you go for it.
- All right.

23:56.561 --> 23:58.477
- You're a very
considerate human.

23:58.521 --> 24:00.396
[humming]

24:00.440 --> 24:02.815
- I am worried
about this handle,

24:02.859 --> 24:04.233
simply because he didn't
put a guard on that.

24:04.277 --> 24:06.026
It's a very skinny handle,

24:06.070 --> 24:08.630
and the profile of that tip
is not made for thrusting.

24:11.409 --> 24:13.451
- [groans]

24:13.494 --> 24:15.744
Cramp.
[chuckles]

24:15.788 --> 24:17.872
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:17.915 --> 24:21.000
- Ten, nine, eight,

24:21.043 --> 24:23.627
seven, six, five,

24:23.671 --> 24:27.798
four, three, two, one.

24:27.842 --> 24:31.218
Bladesmiths, drop your tools,
stop your work.

24:31.262 --> 24:32.595
[applause]
- [bleep] yeah.

24:32.638 --> 24:34.763
Holy [bleep], dude.

24:34.807 --> 24:36.265
<i>- Feel good.
I'm done.</i>

24:36.309 --> 24:38.184
Everything is out of my hands.

24:38.227 --> 24:40.144
<i>I think they'll want
to take turns</i>

24:40.188 --> 24:45.065
swinging it over their head
just because it feels good.

24:45.109 --> 24:49.487
- All right, bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

24:49.530 --> 24:51.113
We're gonna do the tire slice.

24:51.157 --> 24:53.073
I'm gonna take
each of your blades

24:53.117 --> 24:55.242
and attempt to thrust
the tip through

24:55.286 --> 24:58.204
and cut all the way
around these tires.

24:58.247 --> 25:01.081
This will definitely test
the strength and durability

25:01.125 --> 25:03.667
of your weapons.

25:03.711 --> 25:05.169
Morgan, you're up.
Are you ready?

25:05.213 --> 25:08.130
- Yeah.
- Good answer.

25:08.174 --> 25:10.132
<i>- I think my blade
is a little bit sexier</i>

25:10.176 --> 25:11.884
<i>than all of theirs.</i>

25:11.928 --> 25:13.844
It turned out better than
what I was planning on doing.

25:13.888 --> 25:16.847
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:16.891 --> 25:24.813
<i>¶ ¶</i>

25:27.652 --> 25:29.568
- Well, Morgan,
that worked very well.

25:29.612 --> 25:31.320
- Thank you.

25:31.364 --> 25:34.240
- Looking at the edge,
I do see some shiny spots,

25:34.283 --> 25:36.700
so you might have lost
a little bit of your edge.

25:36.744 --> 25:40.329
But overall, it looks like
most of it held up.

25:40.373 --> 25:42.831
Nice job.
- Thank you.

25:42.875 --> 25:44.416
- Travis, you're up.
Are you ready?

25:44.460 --> 25:47.002
- Yep.

25:47.046 --> 25:48.879
<i>Even though this blade
is curved,</i>

25:48.923 --> 25:50.756
<i>I think it will stab very well.</i>

25:50.800 --> 25:54.843
Plus, it has a double guard that
really fits nice in the hand.

25:54.887 --> 25:57.846
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:57.890 --> 26:05.813
<i>¶ ¶</i>

26:09.068 --> 26:11.193
- I was able to have pretty good
control with the handle,

26:11.237 --> 26:14.863
and that recurve, it seemed to
slide through that tire cleanly.

26:14.907 --> 26:17.199
Got a little bit of edge roll,

26:17.243 --> 26:19.410
but overall, nicely done.
- Thank you.

26:19.453 --> 26:21.161
- Tom, you're up.
