26:21.205 --> 26:22.955
- As ready as I'm gonna be.

26:22.999 --> 26:25.583
- That works.

26:25.626 --> 26:27.918
<i>- At this point I've done
everything that I could,</i>

26:27.962 --> 26:30.254
<i>but in general you always
are a little bit nervous</i>

26:30.298 --> 26:33.173
when something you've made
is about to be put to the test.

26:33.217 --> 26:41.140
<i>¶ ¶</i>

26:48.566 --> 26:52.192
- Well, Tom,
your edge held up very well,

26:52.236 --> 26:54.194
but bit of trouble
getting that tip in.

26:54.238 --> 26:55.878
Really had to shove
to get that in there...

26:55.906 --> 26:57.823
And that thin handle...

26:57.867 --> 27:00.492
But everything held together,

27:00.536 --> 27:02.620
and I don't see any shine
on your edge at all.

27:02.663 --> 27:04.163
So good job on that.

27:04.206 --> 27:06.665
- Thank you.
- Smiths, good job.

27:06.709 --> 27:10.294
Now I'm gonna pass you off
to Doug for the next test.

27:10.338 --> 27:12.630
- Bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test.

27:12.673 --> 27:14.590
To test your weapon's edge,

27:14.634 --> 27:16.675
I'll slash through
these jumper cables.

27:16.719 --> 27:19.511
If it's sharp, it should cut
right through cleanly.

27:19.555 --> 27:20.888
Morgan, you're up.

27:20.931 --> 27:22.806
You ready?
- Yeah.

27:22.850 --> 27:25.809
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:25.853 --> 27:31.482
<i>¶ ¶</i>

27:31.525 --> 27:34.026
- Well, Morgan, your edge held.

27:34.070 --> 27:36.320
It cut cleanly
through the cable,

27:36.364 --> 27:38.781
but your handle's a little
on the skinny side,

27:38.824 --> 27:40.616
kind of rolls on the hand.

27:40.660 --> 27:42.951
But nonetheless, it will cut.

27:42.995 --> 27:44.286
Good job.

27:44.330 --> 27:46.580
- Thank you.
- Travis, you're up.

27:46.624 --> 27:48.874
Ready?
- Yep.

27:48.918 --> 27:55.631
<i>¶ ¶</i>

27:55.675 --> 27:57.591
- I like your handle, Travis.
- Thank you.

27:57.635 --> 27:59.009
- When it slashes,

27:59.053 --> 28:01.804
you can almost feel
the curve of your blade.

28:01.847 --> 28:04.431
It's a sharp blade
and for this test, sir,

28:04.475 --> 28:06.058
it will cut.

28:06.102 --> 28:08.185
Good job.
- Thank you.

28:08.229 --> 28:11.063
- Tom, it's your turn.
Are you ready?

28:11.107 --> 28:12.773
- Yes.
[laughs]

28:12.817 --> 28:14.692
- Good answer.

28:14.735 --> 28:22.735
<i>¶ ¶</i>

28:22.993 --> 28:26.745
Tom, your blade definitely
has that nice curve to it.

28:26.789 --> 28:29.206
A little rounded on the handle
here, though, once again.

28:29.250 --> 28:30.708
Even in other movements,

28:30.751 --> 28:33.544
I can feel it
want to roll around.

28:33.587 --> 28:36.213
But it will cut.

28:36.257 --> 28:37.756
<i>- We're all neck and neck.</i>

28:37.800 --> 28:39.591
<i>I mean, like, right there.</i>

28:39.635 --> 28:42.469
I am very interested to hear
what the judges have to say.

28:42.513 --> 28:45.472
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

28:45.516 --> 28:48.058
<i>¶ ¶</i>

28:48.102 --> 28:49.518
- Bladesmiths,

28:49.562 --> 28:52.646
each of you has forged
a beautiful weapon

28:52.690 --> 28:55.691
that performed very well
in our tests.

28:55.735 --> 28:57.276
Unfortunately,

28:57.319 --> 29:01.780
only two of you can move on
to the final round.

29:01.824 --> 29:04.116
The judges have made
a final decision.

29:04.160 --> 29:06.452
It's time for one of you
to surrender his weapon

29:06.495 --> 29:08.036
and leave the Forge.

29:08.080 --> 29:10.789
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

29:18.048 --> 29:19.214
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

29:19.258 --> 29:21.550
- Bladesmiths, our judges

29:21.594 --> 29:25.804
have had to evaluate
every facet of your blades.

29:25.848 --> 29:29.641
Only two of you can move on
to the final round.

29:29.685 --> 29:30.934
The person leaving the Forge...

29:30.978 --> 29:33.103
<i>¶ ¶</i>

29:33.147 --> 29:34.730
Is Tom.

29:34.774 --> 29:37.858
Your blade did not make the cut.

29:37.902 --> 29:39.568
- Tom, you got
a great piece there.

29:39.612 --> 29:41.653
All of the knives
had pros and cons.

29:41.697 --> 29:43.489
Your piece wasn't
developed as much

29:43.532 --> 29:45.574
for the testing
as your competitors

29:45.618 --> 29:47.618
and that showed
in the tire slice.

29:47.661 --> 29:49.620
Had more trouble
with the penetration

29:49.663 --> 29:52.206
<i>and more trouble with
the blade wandering around,</i>

29:52.249 --> 29:53.999
and that's a big reason
we have to let you go.

29:54.043 --> 29:56.627
- That's fair.
Thank you.

29:58.798 --> 30:02.466
- Tom, please surrender
your weapon.

30:02.510 --> 30:04.343
<i>- I feel like I did great.</i>

30:04.386 --> 30:08.847
I made a functional blade
out of a coil spring from a car.

30:08.891 --> 30:10.766
<i>I didn't outright
fail at anything.</i>

30:10.810 --> 30:12.059
I just wasn't quite as good

30:12.102 --> 30:13.519
as the other ones,
so that's okay.

30:13.562 --> 30:14.562
I'd do it again.

30:14.605 --> 30:16.980
[laughs]

30:18.734 --> 30:21.235
<i>¶ ¶</i>

30:21.278 --> 30:23.654
- Morgan, Travis,
congratulations.

30:23.697 --> 30:26.031
You're both moving on
to the final round.

30:26.075 --> 30:28.867
When you arrived here,
you forged blades

30:28.911 --> 30:31.411
in your signature style,
of your own design.

30:31.455 --> 30:35.040
Now we're sending you home
to forge an iconic blade

30:35.084 --> 30:38.710
that is thousands of years old.

30:38.754 --> 30:41.839
<i>¶ ¶</i>

30:41.882 --> 30:42.840
- Oh, yeah.

30:42.883 --> 30:45.759
- The Viking sword.

30:45.803 --> 30:48.720
<i>The Vikings, originating
from Scandinavia,</i>

30:48.764 --> 30:51.765
<i>raided wide areas
of northern and central Europe</i>

30:51.809 --> 30:54.226
<i>from the 8th to 11th centuries.</i>

30:54.270 --> 30:57.271
<i>The Viking sword was derived
from the Roman spatha</i>

30:57.314 --> 31:00.399
<i>and was seen as a matter
of high prestige and wealth.</i>

31:00.442 --> 31:02.359
<i>The large double-edged weapon</i>

31:02.403 --> 31:05.070
<i>was often used in battle
along with the shield.</i>

31:05.114 --> 31:08.198
<i>It often had a fuller running
along the length of the blade,</i>

31:08.242 --> 31:10.742
<i>increasing the strength
and flexibility</i>

31:10.786 --> 31:13.036
<i>while also reducing the weight.</i>

31:13.080 --> 31:15.747
<i>The hilt and pommel
provided balance to the weapon,</i>

31:15.791 --> 31:19.293
<i>helping the swordsman to swing
the blade at his enemy.</i>

31:19.336 --> 31:22.004
<i>This iconic weapon
has been immortalized</i>

31:22.047 --> 31:24.464
<i>in films like "King Arthur."</i>

31:24.508 --> 31:28.218
<i>¶ ¶</i>

31:28.262 --> 31:32.639
It must be a working version
of that deadly weapon.

31:32.683 --> 31:35.100
You will have five days
in your home forge.

31:35.144 --> 31:37.185
At the end of five days,
you will return

31:37.229 --> 31:40.397
and present your finished
Viking swords to our judges,

31:40.441 --> 31:44.026
who will then subject them
to a series of tests.

31:44.069 --> 31:46.029
Only after those tests
are complete

31:46.071 --> 31:49.281
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

31:49.325 --> 31:52.743
who receives a check
for $10,000.

31:52.786 --> 31:55.954
<i>- The Vikings had said
the best blade was quenched</i>

31:55.998 --> 31:58.540
<i>in the piss
of a redheaded virgin.</i>

31:58.584 --> 32:00.083
I don't know
any redheaded virgins,

32:00.127 --> 32:03.170
but I imagine
oil will be just fine.

32:03.213 --> 32:04.379
- Good luck, bladesmiths.

32:04.423 --> 32:05.964
We'll see you in five days.

32:06.008 --> 32:08.425
- Good luck.
- Good luck, man.

32:08.469 --> 32:11.428
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:11.472 --> 32:13.972
<i>¶ ¶</i>

32:14.016 --> 32:16.516
Today is day one
of the Viking sword build,

32:16.560 --> 32:19.811
<i>and just want to get
my layout nice.</i>

32:19.855 --> 32:21.939
<i>Your layout's pretty important.</i>

32:21.982 --> 32:23.690
<i>There's nothing worse
than running around</i>

32:23.734 --> 32:27.152
<i>with a 36-inch piece
of really hot steel</i>

32:27.196 --> 32:30.948
in a non-feng shui
environment.

32:30.991 --> 32:33.784
<i>¶ ¶</i>

32:33.827 --> 32:36.870
I kind of rummaged
through the farm scrapyard.

32:36.914 --> 32:39.581
This is actually
an arm off a chisel plow.

32:39.625 --> 32:42.417
<i>It's spring steel,
tougher than hell.</i>

32:42.461 --> 32:45.963
<i>So I figure
since I have good steel,</i>

32:46.006 --> 32:47.506
I'm not gonna do
a pattern-welded blade.

32:47.549 --> 32:49.257
Strike while it's hot.

32:49.301 --> 32:51.093
<i>I'm gonna do something
that's gonna perform</i>

32:51.136 --> 32:52.886
<i>without the likelihood
of failure.</i>

32:52.930 --> 32:55.597
I think it just kind of laughs
at my hammer at this point.

32:55.641 --> 32:57.516
<i>Day one, I feel good because</i>

32:57.559 --> 32:59.518
essentially
I'm figuring out the tools,

32:59.561 --> 33:01.103
<i>and so tomorrow?</i>

33:01.146 --> 33:03.689
<i>Put them to use.</i>

33:03.732 --> 33:05.941
<i>¶ ¶</i>

33:05.985 --> 33:10.153
- Game plan on day one
is to make my Damascus billet.

33:10.197 --> 33:14.074
What really sets our blades
apart is gonna be the artwork.

33:14.118 --> 33:16.451
I figure if I'm gonna
make a Damascus billet,

33:16.495 --> 33:19.871
I might as well make it
complicated and look nice.

33:19.915 --> 33:24.209
Normally we've got, like,
two guys that do this.

33:24.253 --> 33:25.961
You can actually
see the pattern already.

33:26.005 --> 33:27.629
Those are the actual layers

33:27.673 --> 33:29.381
and what it's gonna look like
when it draws out.

33:29.425 --> 33:31.550
That's looking good.
I like that, I like that a lot.

33:31.593 --> 33:34.553
I'm just gonna clean it
really quick and call it a day.

33:34.596 --> 33:38.557
<i>¶ ¶</i>

33:38.600 --> 33:40.475
- Those little
whooshes are still enough

33:40.519 --> 33:41.852
to take off eyelashes.

33:41.895 --> 33:43.478
Well, day two, I have my steel

33:43.522 --> 33:45.605
in the basic shape
of the Viking sword.

33:45.649 --> 33:48.942
So we're gonna start forging
in the fuller and the bevels.

33:48.986 --> 33:51.403
So the fuller down the middle
makes a lighter, stronger blade,

33:51.447 --> 33:53.989
or a stronger blade
of given weight.

33:54.033 --> 33:55.782
And they're cool.

33:55.826 --> 33:59.911
By the end of the day,
I plan to have a finished blade.

33:59.955 --> 34:01.621
There we go.

34:01.665 --> 34:03.498
What could go wrong, right?

34:03.542 --> 34:05.876
<i>¶ ¶</i>

34:05.919 --> 34:07.961
Everything's lightening up,

34:08.005 --> 34:09.755
and everything's
coming in straight,

34:09.798 --> 34:11.339
so I'm gonna
dangle it in the forge

34:11.383 --> 34:14.176
and quench it once.

34:14.219 --> 34:16.553
<i>I don't know
what's gonna happen here,</i>

34:16.597 --> 34:18.597
<i>and I don't know
what the forge is gonna do</i>

34:18.640 --> 34:20.474
<i>in the vertical position,</i>

34:20.517 --> 34:23.018
and I don't know
if I can get an even heat.

34:23.062 --> 34:25.812
All right, here we go.

34:25.856 --> 34:28.565
I don't know, even, if I'm at
the right temperature.

34:28.609 --> 34:30.484
Oh, that's gonna happen!

34:30.527 --> 34:31.693
Uh-oh.

34:31.737 --> 34:35.197
<i>¶ ¶</i>

34:35.240 --> 34:36.990
Dun-dun-dun.

34:37.034 --> 34:40.243
<i>¶ ¶</i>

34:40.287 --> 34:42.579
Pretty straight.

34:42.623 --> 34:44.456
Ow, still hot.

34:44.500 --> 34:49.795
<i>¶ ¶</i>

34:52.466 --> 34:56.218
It ain't done, but it will kill.

35:05.312 --> 35:06.937
- Today is day three,

35:06.980 --> 35:09.397
and my plan is to finish up
my blade completely.

35:09.441 --> 35:11.900
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:11.944 --> 35:14.277
At the very tip of my blade
my steel didn't forge well,

35:14.321 --> 35:16.404
so I want to draw out
that whole end

35:16.448 --> 35:18.532
so that I can then grind
all of that weld off.

35:18.575 --> 35:21.827
<i>¶ ¶</i>

35:21.870 --> 35:23.411
If I have an uneven heat,

35:23.455 --> 35:25.413
it'll cause my blade
to warp when I quench,

35:25.457 --> 35:27.624
or it'll heat treat unevenly,

35:27.668 --> 35:29.668
which will produce
soft spots in my blade.

35:29.711 --> 35:31.391
This is make or break
moment for any blade.

35:31.421 --> 35:34.131
There's always stuff
that goes wrong.

35:34.174 --> 35:35.507
Ooh.

35:35.551 --> 35:37.134
[bleep].

35:37.177 --> 35:43.014
<i>¶ ¶</i>

35:43.058 --> 35:46.476
Oh, [bleep] it.

35:46.520 --> 35:48.186
That would be it.

35:48.230 --> 35:51.106
So I feel really good
about how hard my blade is,

35:51.150 --> 35:54.359
but I won't really know
until later, for sure.

35:54.403 --> 35:56.862
[rooster crows]

35:56.905 --> 35:58.280
<i>- So it's day four.</i>

35:58.323 --> 36:00.282
<i>My concern is my blade
is not as hard</i>

36:00.325 --> 36:01.908
as it's supposed to be.

36:01.952 --> 36:03.535
I like intentionally
breaking stuff,

36:03.579 --> 36:05.787
not having stuff break on me.

36:05.831 --> 36:09.457
So this morning I'm just
gonna do a few tests.

36:12.588 --> 36:14.129
If anything's gonna happen,

36:14.173 --> 36:16.506
I'm gonna find it
before the judges do.

36:16.550 --> 36:18.175
Nothing like testing.

36:18.218 --> 36:23.138
<i>¶ ¶</i>

36:23.182 --> 36:25.849
I'm no longer concerned
about my steel.

36:25.893 --> 36:28.310
<i>Took quite a bit
to break off that tip,</i>

36:28.353 --> 36:30.770
so it seems tougher than hell.

36:30.814 --> 36:33.106
<i>I am pretty sure
it's gonna withstand anything</i>

36:33.150 --> 36:35.275
the judges throw at it.

36:35.319 --> 36:37.485
[bleep] damn it, knock on wood.

36:37.529 --> 36:38.904
[knocks]

36:38.947 --> 36:40.947
<i>¶ ¶</i>

36:40.991 --> 36:42.824
I made good progress today.

36:42.868 --> 36:46.786
<i>I'm sitting with a very nice,
very symmetric,</i>

36:46.830 --> 36:48.788
<i>and almost finished blade,</i>

36:48.832 --> 36:51.708
and so tomorrow
it's on to handle.

36:51.752 --> 36:55.420
<i>¶ ¶</i>

36:55.464 --> 36:57.130
<i>- Today is day four.</i>

36:57.174 --> 36:59.382
I really need to get my blade
done and presentable,

36:59.426 --> 37:01.885
otherwise I'm screwed.

37:01.929 --> 37:07.557
<i>¶ ¶</i>

37:07.601 --> 37:09.643
Nice and tight.

37:09.686 --> 37:11.937
Let's cut some crap.

37:11.980 --> 37:17.150
<i>¶ ¶</i>

37:17.194 --> 37:19.945
Hmm, [bleep], that sucks.

37:19.988 --> 37:23.531
The delamination, little bit
seems to have separated enough,

37:23.575 --> 37:25.242
got coconut in it.

37:25.285 --> 37:27.953
I really need to figure out
how to get these out.

37:27.996 --> 37:30.914
<i>¶ ¶</i>

37:30.958 --> 37:34.084
I think I might have lost
my heat treat from the weld.

37:34.127 --> 37:37.712
<i>Just in case, I'm gonna have
to re-heat treat my blade.</i>

37:40.259 --> 37:43.301
[exhales]

37:43.345 --> 37:46.930
[bleep] me.

37:46.974 --> 37:49.641
No. [bleep].

37:49.685 --> 37:52.018
I'm trying to heat treat this
with the handle on,

37:52.062 --> 37:54.771
<i>but I can't get
the blade itself hot enough.</i>

37:54.815 --> 37:58.191
It's still flexible,
which is not good.

37:58.235 --> 37:59.985
Salvageable?
No.

38:00.028 --> 38:03.321
Should have just left it.

38:03.365 --> 38:05.991
<i>¶ ¶</i>

38:06.034 --> 38:06.950
[snap]

38:06.994 --> 38:10.203
And that was my blade.

38:10.247 --> 38:12.414
I am so [bleep].

38:12.457 --> 38:14.874
Just broke my blade.

38:14.918 --> 38:17.210
<i>I've got to figure out
something and power through</i>

38:17.254 --> 38:19.129
and turn something in.

38:19.172 --> 38:20.505
[bleep].

38:27.180 --> 38:30.557
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:30.600 --> 38:33.184
- Travis, Morgan, welcome back.

38:33.228 --> 38:35.437
You've had five days
at your home forge

38:35.480 --> 38:37.147
to work on your Viking swords.

38:37.190 --> 38:40.317
Travis, how did it go?
- It was interesting.

38:40.360 --> 38:42.986
<i>You know, I wasn't exactly sure
what steel I was working with,</i>

38:43.030 --> 38:44.696
<i>but I know it's
tougher than hell.</i>

38:44.740 --> 38:46.573
<i>I'm happy with the way
it turned out.</i>

38:46.616 --> 38:48.825
Maybe it's a little heavy,
but it felt good to me,

38:48.869 --> 38:51.119
so we'll see how it does.

38:51.163 --> 38:54.205
- Great.
Morgan, how'd it go?

38:54.249 --> 38:56.583
- I had some stuff go wrong
with the blade.

38:56.626 --> 38:59.294
<i>I had a couple delaminations
in my Damascus.</i>

38:59.338 --> 39:01.880
<i>I went back and I braised them,
I lost my heat treat,</i>

39:01.923 --> 39:03.757
<i>and when that happened
and my blade cracked,</i>

39:03.800 --> 39:06.384
that was pretty rough.

39:06.428 --> 39:08.136
- All right, gentlemen,

39:08.180 --> 39:10.805
your weapons will now be put
through a series of three tests.

39:10.849 --> 39:13.016
Up first is the kill test.

39:13.060 --> 39:14.601
Doug.

39:14.644 --> 39:16.978
- Bladesmiths,
this is the kill test.

39:17.022 --> 39:19.856
The Viking sword was designed
to be a single-handed weapon,

39:19.900 --> 39:22.317
used to breach through
an enemy's defenses,

39:22.361 --> 39:24.778
delivering a thrust,
a chop, and a slice.

39:24.821 --> 39:26.863
To test how lethal
your weapon is

39:26.907 --> 39:28.948
I will breach through
this simulated sword,

39:28.992 --> 39:31.284
and then deliver
a thrust, slice,

39:31.328 --> 39:33.248
and chop
on this ballistics dummy.

39:33.288 --> 39:36.081
Let's see how much lethal damage
your weapon can do.

39:36.124 --> 39:37.499
Travis, you're up.
Are you ready?

39:37.542 --> 39:39.125
- Yep.

39:39.169 --> 39:41.711
<i>- I need Travis' blade
to just fail,</i>

39:41.755 --> 39:44.506
<i>otherwise I'm screwed.</i>

39:46.093 --> 39:49.052
<i>[rock music]</i>

39:49.096 --> 39:53.848
<i>¶ ¶</i>

39:53.892 --> 39:55.475
- Well, Travis,
you weren't kidding

39:55.519 --> 39:56.935
when you said
it was a little bit heavy.

39:56.978 --> 39:58.812
Recovery's
a little bit difficult,

39:58.855 --> 40:01.314
but once you get it going
the sharpness of your edge

40:01.358 --> 40:04.692
<i>definitely will cleave
through anything in its path.</i>

40:04.736 --> 40:07.153
If you had a little bit more
weight in the back over here,

40:07.197 --> 40:08.363
that would have really

40:08.407 --> 40:10.240
definitely
counterbalanced the blade.

40:10.283 --> 40:11.741
But nonetheless,

40:11.785 --> 40:14.869
that's a beautiful-looking
sword.

40:14.913 --> 40:18.289
This, sir, will kill.

40:18.333 --> 40:19.333
- Thank you.

40:19.376 --> 40:20.500
- Morgan, you're next.

40:20.544 --> 40:22.144
You ready?
- Yep.

40:22.170 --> 40:24.170
- Let's do this.
- All right.

40:26.633 --> 40:29.592
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:29.636 --> 40:37.350
<i>¶ ¶</i>

40:37.394 --> 40:39.769
<i>- I was really
striving for perfection.</i>

40:39.813 --> 40:41.771
So you take a risk
and sometimes it pays off

40:41.815 --> 40:43.815
and sometimes it doesn't.

40:43.859 --> 40:46.025
- Okay...

40:46.069 --> 40:47.944
Morgan, there are
a couple of issues

40:47.988 --> 40:50.822
that we have here
with your sword.

40:50.866 --> 40:53.575
Number one, with the handle.

40:53.618 --> 40:56.077
It's loose.

40:56.121 --> 41:00.540
My biggest concern
is on your blade itself.

41:00.584 --> 41:03.543
Not only do I see cracks.

41:03.587 --> 41:08.339
I actually see holes
in your sword.

41:08.383 --> 41:09.466
Uh...

41:09.509 --> 41:11.718
<i>¶ ¶</i>

41:11.761 --> 41:15.263
Morgan, due to the issues
you have with your blade,

41:15.307 --> 41:16.848
for safety reasons

41:16.892 --> 41:18.683
we will not be able
to test your sword.

41:22.314 --> 41:24.647
That being said, though,

41:24.691 --> 41:26.733
thank you for
sticking with the challenge

41:26.776 --> 41:29.944
and presenting us
with a weapon today.

41:29.988 --> 41:32.989
- Gentlemen, because we cannot
test Morgan's sword,

41:33.033 --> 41:36.034
we will not move forward
with any other weapons tests.

41:36.077 --> 41:37.452
-<i> I knew it was coming.</i>

41:37.496 --> 41:38.995
<i>There was no doubts about it,</i>

41:39.039 --> 41:40.914
so, I mean, it kind of sucks,

41:40.957 --> 41:43.958
but, you know, it is what it is.

41:44.002 --> 41:47.504
<i>¶ ¶</i>

41:47.547 --> 41:49.839
- Morgan, Travis,

41:49.883 --> 41:51.843
you had five days
at your home forges

41:51.885 --> 41:54.636
to create your own version
of a Viking sword.

41:54.679 --> 41:58.348
You both made valiant efforts.

41:58.391 --> 42:00.642
Travis, congratulations.

42:00.685 --> 42:02.727
You are the
"Forged in Fire" champion.

42:02.771 --> 42:05.355
<i>[rock music]</i>

42:05.398 --> 42:06.648
- It's been fun, man.

42:06.691 --> 42:09.108
- Yeah.
- Morgan, I'm sorry.

42:09.152 --> 42:11.027
You did not make the cut.

42:11.071 --> 42:13.988
- Morgan, you are one
of the youngest smiths ever

42:14.032 --> 42:15.573
to grace this forge,

42:15.617 --> 42:18.618
but despite that,
you showed so much maturity

42:18.662 --> 42:20.620
from round one,
where you fell behind,

42:20.664 --> 42:23.289
and made it all the way
to the finals.

42:23.333 --> 42:26.125
- Morgan, please
surrender your weapon.

42:26.169 --> 42:27.877
<i>¶ ¶</i>

42:27.921 --> 42:30.421
- Morgan, thank you.
- Thank you.

42:30.465 --> 42:32.924
- Yeah, I definitely
agree with the decision.

42:32.968 --> 42:34.884
<i>You know, I didn't win,
but it's a pretty good feeling</i>

42:34.928 --> 42:36.469
to know that
I can make it this far,

42:36.513 --> 42:38.096
and I'm not that little kid
in the backyard

42:38.139 --> 42:41.099
tinkering around anymore.

42:41.142 --> 42:43.142
- Travis, congratulations.

42:43.186 --> 42:44.936
You are the
"Forged in Fire" champion

42:44.980 --> 42:47.897
and will be receiving
a check for $10,000.

42:47.941 --> 42:52.110
<i>¶ ¶</i>

42:52.153 --> 42:54.279
- You got a very,
very nice looking sword.

42:54.322 --> 42:55.780
<i>- Thank you.</i>

42:55.824 --> 42:57.448
<i>- Travis,
it's a beautiful blade.</i>

42:57.492 --> 42:58.950
It performed very well.

42:58.994 --> 43:00.827
<i>- This was a hell
of an experience.</i>

43:00.870 --> 43:04.414
It really tests a person's
ability to adapt under fire.

43:04.457 --> 43:07.000
<i>¶ ¶</i>
